{"parentUuid":"54e7b5dc-2188-4e3b-b1b1-d5f8c280ddae","isSidechain":false,"message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_018bYfZ92Q6FLrrFuTqhvNBR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"1. Define the problem variables: n is the ploidy (number of chromosome sets), each gamete carries n/2 alleles, F₀ individuals start with exactly one 'a' allele among n total alleles.\n2. Write out the breeding scheme: F₁ comes from F₀ self-crossed; for k ≥ 2, F_k comes from F_(k-1) × F_(k-2).\n3. Define M_k as the maximum possible number of 'a' alleles that an individual in generation F_k can carry.\n4. Set the initial conditions: M₀ = 1 (given F₀ genotype) and M₁ = 2 (selfing of F₀ can combine two gametes each carrying at most one 'a').\n5. Derive the recurrence M_k = min(M_(k-1), n/2) + min(M_(k-2), n/2), where the cap n/2 reflects that any gamete can carry at most n/2 alleles.\n6. State the appearance condition: a fully 'a' genotype (aaa…a) can appear in F_k iff M_k ≥ n (i.e., the cell can be filled with n 'a' alleles).\n7. Translate \"minimum generation = 8\" into two conditions: M₇ < n (no all-'a' yet by generation 7) AND M₈ ≥ n (all-'a' becomes possible in generation 8).\n8. Note the biological constraint that n must be even (so meiosis halves the chromosome set cleanly).\n9. For each candidate even n, iterate the recurrence to compute M₀, M₁, …, M₈, applying the gamete cap n/2 at each step.\n10. Test small even values of n in increasing order (n = 20, 22, 24, 26, 28, …) and at each one check whether M₇ < n and M₈ ≥ n hold simultaneously.\n11. Identify and report the smallest even n that satisfies both conditions as the answer."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":6,"cache_creation_input_tokens":58625,"cache_read_input_tokens":16143,"output_tokens":11482,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,